    value: 무신 정중부(鄭仲孚) 등이 집권하기 위하여 특별히 의정당(義政堂)을 설치하여 중방(重房)이라 하였다.
english:
  title: A Second Memorial
  author: Jo Jun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    From the end of the Chosŏn age in the east, the lands fragmented into seventy kingdoms, which consolidated into the Three Han. Wars blazed without cease, and the common people's blood soaked the earth through the Two Hans, Three Kingdoms, Six Dynasties, Sui, and Tang, until the Five Dynasties—never to rest. Our Great Ancestor received the Mandate of Heaven and rose to rescue the land. With armor upon his body and in wind and rain, he marched north and south until he achieved unity, which has endured five hundred years. In that time, the false Shin usurped the throne and the royal temples ceased their offerings. Yet Your Highness has now continued the broken line of thirty-one generations, and the hundred million souls of Three Han watch with eager eyes, hoping for Your Highness's restoration.

    Your Highness's person is where Heaven and the High Lord have cast their care, where the Great Ancestor and sainted emperors have placed their trust, where mountains, rivers, and spirits find their anchor, where millions of lives are bound. The height exceeds even Sung Mountain's pinnacle, the burden surpasses even Tai Mountain's weight. When one word falls from your lips, it is as thunder rolling across heaven—all Three Han hear it. When one act is performed, it is as sun and moon rising in the sky—all Three Han behold it.

    Reverence is the foundation upon which emperors build sainthood; justice is the root from which they bring order. I beg Your Highness to fear above the gaze of Heaven and below the eyes of multitudes. When you reward one person, tremble lest it displease the High Lord's heart that blesses the good. When you punish one person, tremble lest it offend the High Lord's mirror that condemns the wicked. Let the multitude rejoice before you reward; let the multitude abandon before you punish. Guard even a torn garment; spare even a single smile. When appointing an official, think: "Is this man truly a gentleman who can order Heaven's work and nourish Heaven's people without drawing Heaven's blame?"

    Though they were companions from your time as heir, fear the High Lord and grant them no private favors. Though they are your kin, fear the High Lord and elevate them through no secret channel. Labor earnestly to seek the wise and broaden your wisdom. Love learning and deepen your virtue. Receive the common people with propriety. Serve the Queen Mother with filial piety. In banishing evil, harbor no doubt. When orders are issued, ensure they are executed.

    Within the nine-layered palace, remember your people lack shelter from wind and rain. At the eight precious dishes, recall your people want for even dregs. When you don fresh garments, think of the silkworm wives standing bare. Follow Great Yu who wore coarse cloth. At royal banquets, remember the starving farmers. Emulate Emperor Wen who ate but one meat. Exalt frugality and warn against extravagance. Conserve resources and love your people. Cherish forthright speech and despise flattery. Draw near the gentlemen and distance the petty men.

    Those who speak without restraint, face their rulers in the court without evasion, and know only the state—forgetting their own houses—these are gentlemen. If Your Highness embraces and trusts them, the governance of Yao and Shun can be achieved while seated, and the legacy of the Great Ancestor can be inherited and flourish.

    But those who seek favor for their in-laws, insist on repaying grudges, and when they hear of the people's suffering, coldly say, "What has it to do with my heart?"—those who see their ruler's faults yet stay silent, saying "The mouth is disaster's gate"—those who merely practice flattery to steal wealth and know only their houses while forgetting the state—these are petty men. Should Your Highness delight in employing them, the downfall of Jie and Zhou awaits, and the Great Ancestor's achievements will crumble.

    The Two Emperors and Three Kings all pursued learning. Perfect stillness and holding to the mean were Yao and Shun's learning; establishing the center and the pole were Tang and King Wu's learning. I beseech Your Highness to select great scholars versed in the classics and histories with correct hearts, and have them attend in rotation, discussing the classics and investigating the principles of governance, to perfect your learning in brilliance and illumination.

    Let the historians also attend in rotation, recording left words and right deeds in full, to instruct ten thousand generations. Establish a lecture hall for the Crown Prince, with the greatest scholars of our age as teachers and virtuous men versed in the classics as advisors, dwelling together day and night, expounding the scriptures to clarify the learning of proper foundations and pure sources.

    The army is led by the Eight Guards, the Eight Guards commanded by the Military Register. The forty-two garrison commands field twelve million troops. Squads have commanders, fives have sergeants, up to generals—all in hierarchy to strengthen the guards and repel foreign invasion. Since we entered service to Yuan, long peace has reigned. Officials have grown lax, warriors soft. The guards lack men. Thus we appointed protect-generals and lesser ranks among the close attendants and loyal brave, replacing the guards' function. Now the Eight Guards of our ancestors stand empty, merely wasting the state's stipends.

    Yet the Tatar horsemen, Mongol riders, special guards—these loyal servants labor day and night without rest, yet receive not a measure of stipend, while those eating the pay of the forty-two commands' five and ten officers are either weak youth or merchants and slaves. Some eat their stipends yet abandon their posts; others labor faithfully yet starve. Is this the ancestors' intent of valuing loyalty and stipends?

    I humbly urge Your Highness to merge the close attendants into the Left and Right Guards, the Gate Keepers into the Gate Guard, the Shield Bearers into the Patrol Guard, and the Loyal Brave into the Divine Tiger Guard. Let all horsemen unite by type into their respective guards, rotating daily service, inspecting diligence, and appointing each by their guard's ranks of protect-general down to sergeant and commander, so that they eat their stipends and labor faithfully. Then men will gladly take office and the state will save resources, the guards will be strong and military readiness secured.

    The Steward of Quarters was anciently the Director of Lodging; now it is the Bureau of Setup. The Steward of Provisions was anciently the Director of Food; now it is the Bureau of Meals. Yet now the Setup Bureau eats its stipends while neglecting its duties, while the Quarters Steward labors without stipend. The Provisions Bureau and below are the same. I urge merging the Quarters Steward, Provisions Steward and like offices into the Six Bureaus, restoring the ancient way and reforming modern corruption. Then names and reality align and duties proceed.

    Without merit, one receives no marquisate—this is our law. Kim, the Chancellor, Fu-shik ended the usurpation and pacified the Western Capital, so we raised him to Marquis of Nangnan. Kim, the Premier, Pang-kyŏng punished the rebellion of Tamna and brought justice to the Eastern Barbarians, so we raised him to Duke of Sang-nak. Hereafter, let no chancellor who is not a Restorer of Peace and Order merit receive a peerage.

    Eunuchs from our founding through the Kyŏngnung reign could not hold office. Recently they have participated in state affairs through their role bearing imperial commands. This does not honor the court. Hereafter, follow the Kyŏngnung precedent: do not permit eunuchs to hold court rank.

    The Military Weapons Bureau and the Works Bureau have pressing duties but few men. Let the upper generals and staff generals concurrently serve as judges and registrars. Then salaries are not wasted yet duties are fulfilled. Apply this principle of concurrent service to other busy bureaus for efficiency.

    Schools are the fountainhead of moral transformation. National order and disorder, success and failure in governance—all stem from here. Recently, due to war, schools have fallen into ruin, overgrown with weeds. Petty men wearing the scholar's name avoid military service. In the fifth and sixth months they gather children to read Tang and Song quatrains for fifty days, calling it "summer studies." Magistrates regard this indifferently, never giving it thought. Yet we wish for scholars versed in the classics with perfected conduct to strengthen our state. How can this be achieved?

    I urge Your Highness to appoint diligent, capable, widely-learned men as instructors, dispatching one to each of the five circuits. Let them travel the prefectures and counties, with the local schools providing their mounts and supplies. Also appoint idle scholars from prefectures and counties as local instructors, requiring students to read constantly the Four Books and Five Classics—not poetry and prose. Let instructors tour their circuit, establish strict curricula, personally debate students, examine their understanding, record names in registers, encourage and promote them to become genuine talent. When such men show great success, advance them without regard to rank. Those unable to teach with results should face punishment.

    Mencius said: "Of three forms of unfilialness, leaving no heir is worst," for it means the sacrifices end. Thus the ancients, when parents passed, buried them in the fields, performed the spirit-pacifying rite, and honored them in the ancestral temple—treating the dead as if living.

    Our eastern family temples long fell into disuse. Now from the capital through prefectures and counties, all with means build spirit shrines called "protective sanctuaries."—these are remnants of family temple practice. Alas! To abandon parents' remains on the ground without a family temple to honor them—how can we know where their spirits dwell? This is not a child's heart. Yet habit has made it seem natural, and few pause to consider.

    I urge from now forward to follow Zhu Xi's Family Rituals entirely: those of rank Chief and above sacrifice three generations; those of sixth rank and above sacrifice two generations; those of seventh rank below and commoners sacrifice only parents. Choose a clean room and make a spirit-shrine, placing the spirit tablet there with west as the place of honor. Make offerings at new moon and full moon. Make reports upon entering and leaving. Present new foods when they appear. Sacrifice on death anniversaries. On death anniversaries, riding out or receiving guests is forbidden—conduct yourself as if in mourning. Three times yearly at festivals and Cold Food, climbing to graves follows common practice to deepen the reverence for ancestors. Violators shall be judged unfilial.

    The saying goes: "Generous stipends to the loyal move men to service." Thus ancients from ministers down to clerks all valued their stipends. Those in court were never moved to seek private gain but gave their whole heart to public duty. But since powerful families began accumulating land, taxes decline yearly and stipends shrink constantly. The stipend system our ancestors established becomes mere form. Let the authorities consult ancient precedent and enrich stipends. Then scholars will have steadfast hearts and honor can flourish.

    The eight counties of Kyŏnggi suffer heavy taxes and corvée, yet these fall under no royal department nor the provincial inspector's authority, nor have magistrates to propagate order. Taxes are unequal, levies endless, and people cannot live. They have nowhere to appeal. I urge Your Highness to follow the example of other circuits: station fifth or sixth rank officials in each county, have the Kaesŏng Mansion evaluate their performance to determine promotions and demotions.

    Recently, military appointments ignore merit—any premier is promptly dispatched. This produces poor oversight, the enemy grows stronger, and prefectures are devastated. The ancients said: "A ruler who cannot choose generals gives his nation to the enemy; a general who knows not war gives his ruler to the enemy." Selecting generals and controlling the Japanese is an urgent matter today. I urge the Evaluation Council and censors to each nominate those of established prestige and virtue as commanders to manage military affairs.

    When military authority fragments, orders lose force. Now one circuit has three commanders—this is not ancient practice. From today onward, save for the east, west, and north fronts, dispatch one commander per circuit and abolish the rest.

    The army is the people's lifeline and the state's great concern, protecting the throne and eliminating chaos. Our Five Armies and forty-two garrison commands are descended from the Han's North and South Armies and Tang's garrison troops. When the Khitan and Jin, bordering us, set up a Jin emperor as their son and eyed the realm, they sought friendship with us, but our Great Ancestor refused them. He captured three emperors of the Liao and Song, his prestige shook the world, and none dared encroach—all because our ancestors understood military governance and law.

    In recent times, military organization has greatly decayed. Thirty years of warfare has left military authority in chaos. We employ commanders without skill and soldiers untrained. They flee at rumors, leaving ten thousand leagues of bleached bones. A mere Japanese rabble becomes our scourge—is this not heartbreaking? I urge from now that idle officials of fourth rank and above be assigned to the Three Armies with commanders and officers, while fifth rank and below serve the garrison commands under the Military Register, so that upper and lower support each other, organization connects, military authority flows from one source, and all hearts unite. Then with firm commands and trained troops, a million men move as body commanding arm, arm commanding finger. What walls cannot hold? What battle cannot be won?

    Recent traitors have corrupted governance. Men without general's merit hold key posts while those laboring a hundred battles await new assignments. Rewards and punishments lack order; troops lose heart; nowhere achieves success. I urge that henceforth those who shatter enemy formations, behead generals, capture flags, or labor a hundred times receive true appointments: the greatest as upper protect-general, then protect-general and major, down to commander and officer, rewarding enemy-breaking valor. Then men love their commanders and die for their lords.

    When recently the righteous rose to end chaos, grant rank and reward to those who served militarily to encourage others. The state selects provincial inspectors and magistrates to govern the five circuits, yet the east, west, and north fronts alone follow old ways, untouched by royal transformation. I urge establishing inspectors as in other circuits, having them tour prefectures and counties, promoting and demoting military and civil officials.

    Recently post-stations have fallen into decay. Relay service and route-guidance have burdened prefectures until people flee. To restore prefecture livelihood, we must first relieve the post-stations. Though we established post commanders to settle stations, one man cannot manage alone, so each station has private staff as eyes and ears. But lacking official dispatch, people disrespect them and stations suffer. I urge appointing a fifth or sixth rank assistant at each station, nominated as magistrates are, given half-seal, so that capable assistants making stations flourish can be reported by inspectors to fill magistrate vacancies, receive capital appointment as honor, while remote stations' assistants are nominated by inspectors.

    The ever-level storehouse and community storehouse are long strategies for famine relief. Geng Shouzhang's ever-level storehouse and Changsun Ping's community storehouse plans descended from Zhou's Delegation Ministry. Any ruler must prioritize this. Last year in high summer we raised armies; moreover, Japanese raiders came, farming was delayed, harvests failed. This year water flooded again, and the southeast prefectures are desolate. We must consider famine relief.

    Since the state abolished private fields, wealth is stored everywhere. I urge establishing ever-level storehouses in all prefectures and counties, following recent Evaluation Council proposals on gathering and dispersing by abundance and scarcity. I hear Yang-kuang Circuit already established such storehouses—let all circuits follow this. Magistrates failing to comply shall be punished.

    Food is the people's heaven; grain comes from oxen. Thus we established the Animal Slaughter Prohibition Bureau to honor farming and nourish the people. The Tatars substitute ox-slaughter for plowing, especially in the northwest. Every prefecture inn kills oxen for guests with no prohibition. I urge the Animal Slaughter Bureau and magistrates to enforce prohibitions. Those capturing violators and reporting them receive the criminal's property as reward; violators face death sentences.

    When prefectures demand draft animals for formal meals and official travelers, even during farming season they drive peasants through brambles on hunts lasting months. Farming is lost and the people starve—this is the cause. Poultry and swine raised in pens harm no one. I urge establishing two fowl and swine farms in Kyŏnggi: one managed by the Imperial Stables Bureau for temple sacrifices, one by the Culinary Bureau for court and guests. All prefectures and posts should raise them carefully without harming offspring. Within years, supplies will suffice for sacrifices and guests, people's needs will be met, and hunting will not waste farming.

    Annually the Culinary Bureau sends men to the circuits overseeing interior ceramic production, one year per circuit. Under guise of public service, officials profit privately, exploiting in countless ways. A single circuit requires eighty or ninety pack oxen, disturbing all they pass. Yet what reaches the capital is but one hundredth; the rest is private theft—the corruption is extreme. Feather, arrow-shaft, and bamboo requisitions also burden the people greatly. I urge from now that all bureaus cease rural requisitions, presenting all such matters to the central authority. The Evaluation Council directs provincial inspectors, inspectors distribute to counties, who collect directly per documents. This will greatly ease the people.

    Soldiers fighting Japanese and soldiers killing bandits obtain horses, weapons, and goods. Local officials everywhere demand investigation like stolen goods, confiscating all for the capital, hoping for great rewards. This deceives the ruler, poisons the people, demoralizes soldiers, and strengthens the enemy—poor policy indeed. I urge that henceforth circuit commanders breaking enemies merely present heads; military and civilian captures from Japanese goods remain unseized. Codify this so people desire profit and fight boldly. Violators face corruption charges from the Censor's office within and provincial inspectors without.

    Premiers are second only to rulers, sharing heaven's position and deputizing heaven's work. Their honor is without parallel. If they sin, dismissal is proper, retirement is proper, even death is proper—but to order lowly officials to bind them, shackle them, behead and expose them, leaving them unburied is grievous. During Han Wendi's reign, Jia Yi memorialized against punishing officials above the fifth rank; the emperor deeply accepted this, and thereafter all erring ministers took their own lives with honor, never humiliated. Thus the great officers of Han felt shame speaking others' faults, establishing Han's four-hundred-year tradition of propriety.

    I urge that henceforth, though high ministers of both offices commit capital crimes, save for rebellion and treason, follow Wendi's precedent, never apply public execution, establishing our nation's noble treatment of high ministers.

    The Book of Documents says: "Punishment does not extend to heirs." The Tradition says: "Criminals are not extended to their families." Thus Shun slew Gun but elevated Yu; King Wu slew Zhou but enfeoffed Wu-geng—the very heart of heaven and earth creating life.

    Yet in recent times, we kill like eating, fear leaving descendants, grow increasingly harsh. I urge that henceforth all criminals follow the three ancient sage-kings: neither wives nor children shall be condemned, revealing our state's compassion.

    On litigation and caution, even King Wen dared not fully know—this established Zhou's order. Chen Ping knew not the numbers of money and grain; scholars called this knowing a premier's role—he did not intrude on others' duties.

    Our dynasty's system: the Central Authority totals all duties and issues commands; the Censor's office inspects all officials and rectifies customs; the Legal Ministry distinguishes right and wrong, deciding cases. Yet recently greedy schemers deceive the palace, exploit the Central Authority. Lawsuits pile like clouds. Between dispatches, procrastination and negligence multiply, overburdening the system—not the original intent of divided offices. I urge that plaintiffs petition their respective authorities, all direct palace and Central Authority submission forbidden, thus honoring the palace and strengthening the Central Authority.

    All profit and interest arise from one principal and one profit. Recently merchants seek profit alone—one principal's interest sometimes becomes tenfold. Debtors sell wives and children, never repaying. The state already has prohibitions. Yet the Provisions Bureau's grain interest multiplies endlessly, causing debtors to lose homes and livelihood—not the state's care for the people. I urge no taking beyond one principal and one profit. Three offices and six ministries officials regularly visit subordinate bureaus, checking reports, auditing accounts, reviewing calculations. Let no decline occur. Those not obeying the law face the Censor's office correction: major crimes result in demotion or exclusion from reappointment; minor crimes face beatings and return to duty.

    For all great and small officials within and without, after appointment, some delay days before taking office, neglecting public business. Documents and funds become tools for corrupt clerks. This is a grave corruption and unfilial service. I urge that except for censors and political ministries, other capital and provincial officials, after appointment, have three days for capital officials, ten days for provincial officials to thank the throne before taking office, called "acting on authority," confronting old and new, clearly exchanging documents and funds with receipts for evaluation. After thanks, they receive permanent appointment. Violations are strictly punished by the capital's Censor's office and provincial inspectors.

    Recently discipline has collapsed. Prefectural clerks falsely claim military merit for offices; others hide under miscellaneous exams to evade local service; others corrupt officials through influence. This makes prefectures empty and eight circuits barren. I urge that even for three sons and an only child, those three or four generations evaded service without real documents, or claimed military service exemption without genuine exceptional merit or merit certificates, or took miscellaneous exams without being products of the National Academy, Civil Service, Legal, or Medical schools—after adding official ranks, compel them to their original posts to fill prefectures. From now, prefectural clerks exempt through civil service or miscellaneous exams shall not be permitted, making this eternal law.
  footnotes:
    - The 'heavy chambers' (重房) were special councils established during the military dictatorships, particularly by Chŏng Chung-bu. The author critiques how incompetent men occupied such powerful positions while competent military officers were neglected.
    - The reference to Geng Shouzhang and Changsun Ping concerns historical Chinese administrators who developed granary systems during times of agricultural stress—these models are being proposed as solutions for the Chosŏn state.
    - The author frequently alludes to classical Chinese exemplars—Great Yu's frugality, Emperor Wen's self-restraint, King Wu's mercy to the defeated—to establish moral precedent for the new Korean ruler.
